### 4.3. Type C\_{n}

The only minuscule parabolic of type C is P\_{1}. Cosets wP\_{1}\in W(C\_{n})/P\_{1} are identified with [n]\sqcup-[n] via wP\_{1}\mapsto w(1). Hence, the polytope associated to (C\_{n},P\_{1}) is given by the *cross polytope*

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
|  | \Diamond\_{n}=\mathrm{conv}(\pm e\_{i}:i\in[n]). |  |

All pairs (\pm e\_{i},\pm e\_{j}) for i\neq j form edges on \Diamond\_{n}. On the other hand, 2e\_{i} is an element of the type C\_{n} root system. In other words, all possible subpolytopes of \Diamond\_{n} are strong matroids, and all subdivisions of \Diamond\_{n} are strong matroidal. In particular, there are no strong exchange type C\_{n} equations, and the Coxeter Dressian \operatorname{Dr}(C\_{n},P\_{1}) is exactly the secondary fan of \Diamond\_{n}.

### 4.4. Type D\_{n}

Recall that in type D\_{n}, the Weyl group is the intersection of the alternating group with the hyperoctahedral group. There are three minuscule parabolic subgroups P\_{1},P\_{n-1}, and P\_{n}. Note that the last two are isomorphic as subgroups of D\_{n}, and they were studied in [16].